// engine-011-internal-rule — `internal:rule=` prefix on composite state-child (§51.0.O).
//
// Demonstrates A5-7 internal-vs-external transition surface (S67 amendment,
// SPEC §51.0.O) — composite state-children MAY declare two kinds of
// outgoing transitions:
//
//   - Canonical `rule=...`  → EXTERNAL transition. Composite exits (fires
//     <onTransition> handlers + history write if `history` is set + inner
//     engine suspends), then re-enters if target is the same composite.
//
//   - `internal:rule=...`   → INTERNAL transition. Composite does NOT exit.
//     Inner-engine lifecycle preserved. No history write/read. No outer
//     <onTransition> fire.
//
// Both prefixes may coexist on the same composite — different targets in
// each declare different semantics (see <Playing> below).
//
// `internal:rule=` is LEGAL ONLY on composite state-children (those with
// a nested <engine> body). Otherwise the typer fires E-INTERNAL-RULE-NOT-
// COMPOSITE per §34 — on a non-composite state-child the inner/outer
// distinction is meaningless.
//
// v1 implementation state (2026-05-11, Wave 2.2 SHIPPED):
//   - Parser captures `internalRule: EngineRuleForm` on each state-child
//     (engine-statechild-parser.ts).
//   - Typer (SYM PASS 11) fires E-INTERNAL-RULE-NOT-COMPOSITE on non-
//     composite state-children carrying internal:rule=.
//   - Codegen emits a sibling __scrml_engine_<varName>_internal_transitions
//     const per engine with any internal:rule= (tree-shaken when absent).
//   - Runtime _scrml_engine_direct_set / _scrml_engine_advance check the
//     internal table FIRST. Internal-legal targets take the internal path
//     (cell value updates with no subscriber fire → variant-guard dispatcher
//     does not re-render the arm → inner engine lifecycle preserved; no
//     <onTransition> hook fires; no timer arm/clear; no history-cell write).
//     Both helpers return true on external commit, false on internal —
//     codegen gates the post-commit hook-firing call on that boolean.
//   - Test coverage: compiler/tests/unit/engine-a7-internal-rule.test.js §1-§7
//     (typer at §A5-3.2, codegen at §7).
//
// This sample is the canonical internal:rule= surface adopters reach for.

<program>
${
    type AppMode:enum  = { Title, Playing }
    type PlayMode:enum = { Exploring, Battle }
}

<engine for=AppMode initial=.Title>
    <Title rule=.Playing></>

    // <Playing> below: rule=.Title is the EXTERNAL transition (exits composite
    // to Title); internal:rule=.Playing is an INTERNAL self-loop that preserves
    // the inner engine's lifecycle. Both may coexist on the same composite.
    <Playing rule=.Title internal:rule=.Playing>
        <engine for=PlayMode initial=.Exploring>
            <Exploring rule=.Battle></>
            <Battle rule=.Exploring></>
        </>
    </>
</>

<div class="game">
    <h1>App: ${@appMode.variant}</>
    <button onclick=${@appMode = AppMode.Playing}>Start</>
    <button onclick=${@appMode = AppMode.Title}>Quit</>
</div>
</program>
